Chapter 3 – Part 1: Jinja For Loops and Conditional Statements

Now we render multiple items dynamically using:
      {% for %}
      
      {% if %}

# What the Route Does
      @app.route('/posts')
      def showPosts():

This route:
Creates a list of dictionaries
Sends it to the template
Sends a boolean flag border

The Data Structure
      myPosts = [
          {
              'title': 'Finibus Bonorum et Malorum',
              'body': 'Lorem ipsum...'
          },
          ...
      ]

This is:  List → containing → Dictionaries

Very important concept.
Later this will become:
Database query → returning → list of model objects
Same pattern. Different source.

# posts.html Breakdown
      {% extends "base.html" %}
      {% block content %}
      <h1>{{ info.heading }}</h1>
      
      {% for post in posts %}

What this means:
Loop over every item in posts.

For each item:
Store it temporarily in variable post

Accessing Dictionary Values
      <h2>{{ post.title }}</h2>
      <p>{{ post.body }}</p>

Jinja lets you use dot notation:
post.title
post.body
Even though internally it’s a dictionary.

Conditional Logic
      {% if border %}
        <hr>
      {% else %}
        ____post ends here
      {% endif %}

Because in route:
border = False

The template sees:
border == False

So it prints:
____post ends here

If changed:
border = True
Now it prints <hr> after every post.

Full Execution Flow
User visits /posts
Flask creates list myPosts
Sends it to template as posts
Template loops through each post
For each iteration:
Renders title
Renders body
Runs conditional
Final HTML sent to browser

Mental Model
Python list → passed to template → loop → render each item

